===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|人|水|人|t1=person|t2=water|t3=person|ls=p}} – two people fleeing with their backs to a flood ({{zh-ref|Yu Xingwu, 1999}}).

Some oracle bone script variants are written identically to {{zh-l|*化}} (one upright person and one upside-down person). {{zh-ref|Meng (2022)}} suggests that this variant uses {{zh-l|*化}} as a phonetic component due to their phonological connection in Old Chinese.

''{{w|Shuowen}}'', without access to oracle bone script, considered it a {{liushu|p|nocap=1}} of cracks formed on a heated tortoise shell or bone during divination.

===Etymology===
Compare {{cog|cdm|ह्रावःसा||to forebode; to portend ill fortune|tr=hrawʔ‑}}.

